items.title: Fresh search for wreckage of missing MH370 flight to resume within weeks
items.standfirst: The Malaysian government confirmed a 55-day seabed search of "target areas" will restart on December 30.
items.content: T he deep-sea search for the wreckage of Malaysia Airlines Flight 370, which has been missing for more than 11.5 years, will resume in a matter of weeks.The Malaysian government confirmed a 55-day seabed search of "target areas" will restart on December 30.US robotics company Ocean Infinity will lead the search in areas deemed to have the "highest probability of locating the aircraft", Malaysia's Ministry of Transport confirmed in a statement.READ MORE: Robert's thumb was amputated 14 years ago. It sparked a legal nightmareREAD MORE: Trump tells Somali migrants he doesn't want them in US"Ocean Infinity has confirmed with the Government of Malaysia that it will recommence seabed search operations for a total of 55 days, to be conducted intermittently," the statement said."The latest development underscores the Government of Malaysia's commitment in providing closure to the families affected by this tragedy."Ocean Infinity and Malaysia's government reached a "no find, no fee" agreement in March this year to resume the search for the missing flight.The company will be paid A$110 million only if wreckage is discovered.A private search in 2018 by Ocean Infinity also found nothing. The Boeing 777 plane vanished from radar shortly after taking off on March 8, 2014, carrying 239 people, including six Australians, on a flight from Malaysia's capital, Kuala Lumpur, to Beijing.Satellite data showed the plane turned from its flight path and headed south to the far-southern Indian Ocean, where it is believed to have crashed.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. items.title: One dead, two injured as police carry out manhunt after NSW shooting
items.standfirst: A man has died, and two are injured following a shooting on a property in NSW's north-east.
items.content: A man is on the run after a man was shot dead and two others were injured following a shooting on a property in NSW's north-east. A police operation commenced after reports of a shooting on Tyalgum Road at Eungella about 1.25pm.Officers were told two men - aged 41 and 38 - were allegedly shot by another who fled the scene with a fourth man.READ MORE: Further 775 charges over illegal recordings in hospital toiletsParamedics treated the 41-year-old man for a gunshot wound, however, he died at the scene.He is yet to be formally identified.Shortly after, police were informed of a second incident on the same road after a 45-year-old man was allegedly hit by a car.He is being treated at Gold Coast University Hospital and remains under police supervision. The 38-year-old man subsequently sought treatment at hospital for a gunshot wound.READ MORE: Deadly hidden health risks of festivals revealedPolice are now waiting to speak with the 38-year-old and 45-year-old to establish the circumstances surrounding their injuries.Police are working to locate the fourth person, believed to be aged 37.The road has been closed, and police remain on-site searching the area with police dogs. Anyone with information should call Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000 or make an online report. Sign up here to receive our daily newsletters and breaking news alerts, sent straight to your inbox.

items.title: NSW Police Minister's driver charged with high-range drink driving
items.standfirst: Trevor Daley was spotted by passing cars driving dangerously yesterday before blowing three-and-a-half times the legal limit.
items.content: The driver for the NSW Police Minister has been charged with high-range drink driving after blowing three-and-a-half times the legal limit.Trevor Daley, 55, was arrested near Bemboka on the Snowy Mountains Highway after he allegedly blew a .18 breath test, which is around three-and-a-half times the legal limit. READ MORE: Rolls-Royce car worth $600,000 among luxury goods seized by police in Sydney raidsDaley is the driver for Police Minister Yasmin Catley and was bound to pick her up this morning for the opening of the new Bega Police Station. "The circumstances are very concerning. It is illegal to drink and drive, and no one is above the law," Catley said.The Minister was not in the car at the time of the arrest.READ MORE: Bruce Lehrmann loses bid to clear name on Brittany Higgins rape claimShe had flown to Bega with the Police Commissioner, Mal Lanyon.She chose not to comment when asked if Daley remained her driver. Catley has been the Police Minister for more than two years, and each holiday season has been at the forefront of delivering warnings about drink driving.Daley told 9News he would not be making any comment.He is scheduled to face court just before Christmas.
